{"title_page": "Amul Thapar", "text_new": "{{Short description|American judge}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=July 2018}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name         = Amul Thapar\n| image        = Amul Thapar.jpg\n| office       = Judge of the [[United States Court of Appeals for the Sixth Circuit]]\n| appointer    = [[List of federal judges appointed by Donald Trump|Donald Trump]]\n| term_start   = May 25, 2017\n| term_end     =\n| predecessor  = [[Boyce F. Martin Jr.]]\n| successor    =\n| office1      = Judge of the [[United States District Court for the Eastern District of Kentucky]]\n| appointer1   = [[List of federal judges appointed by George W. Bush|George W. Bush]]\n| term_start1  = January 4, 2008\n| term_end1    = May 30, 2017\n| predecessor1 = [[Joseph Martin Hood]]\n| successor1   = [[Robert E. Wier]]\n| office2      = [[United States Attorney]] for the [[United States District Court for the Eastern District of Kentucky|Eastern District of Kentucky]]\n| president2   = [[George W. Bush]]\n| term_start2  = March 20, 2006\n| term_end2    = January 2008\n| predecessor2 = [[Gregory F. Van Tatenhove]]\n| successor2   = [[Kerry B. Harvey]]\n| birth_name   = Amul Roger Thapar\n| birth_date   = {{Birth date and age|1969|04|29}}\n| birth_place  = [[Troy, Michigan|Troy]], [[Michigan]], U.S.\n| death_date   =\n| death_place  =\n| education    = [[Boston College]] ([[Bachelor of Science|BS]])<br>{{nowrap|[[UC Berkeley School of Law]] ([[Juris Doctor|JD]])}}\n| party        =\n}}\n'''Amul Roger Thapar''' (born April 29, 1969) is a [[United States federal judge|United States Circuit Judge]] of the [[United States Court of Appeals for the Sixth Circuit]]. He is a former [[United States federal judge|United States District Judge]] of the [[United States District Court for the Eastern District of Kentucky]] and former [[United States Attorney]] for the Eastern District of Kentucky. Thapar was the first South Asian federal judge in American history.  He was also President Trump's first Court of Appeals appointment and Trump's second judicial appointment after Justice [[Neil Gorsuch]]. Thapar is frequently discussed as a short-lister for the Supreme Court of the United States.\n\n== Early life and education ==\nThapar has lived most of his life in the midwest.<ref name=\"scotusblog1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.scotusblog.com/2018/07/potential-nominee-profile-amul-thapar/ |title=Potential nominee profile: Amul Thapar |publisher=SCOTUSblog |date=2018-07-03 |accessdate=2019-09-16}}</ref> He was born in [[Troy, Michigan|Troy]], [[Michigan]] to parents who immigrated from [[India]]. He was raised in [[Toledo, Ohio]],<ref name=\"SCOTUSblog\">{{cite web |title=Potential nominee profile: Amul Thapar |url=http://www.scotusblog.com/2018/07/potential-nominee-profile-amul-thapar/ |website=[[SCOTUSblog]] |accessdate=July 4, 2018 |date=July 3, 2018}}</ref> where his father, Raj Thapar, owns a heating and air-conditioning supply business.<ref name=\"Courier-Journal December 2016\">{{cite web |title=Ky judge on Trump's short list for high court |url=https://www.courier-journal.com/story/news/politics/2016/12/09/ky-judge-trumps-short-list-high-court/95139578/ |website=The Courier-Journal |accessdate=July 4, 2018 |language=en}}</ref> Thapar worked for his father's business driving the truck.<ref name=\"realclearpolitics1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.realclearpolitics.com/articles/2018/07/03/amul_thapar_trump_countrys_perfect_scotus_choice_137420.html|title=Amul Thapar: Trump Country's Perfect SCOTUS Choice &#124; RealClearPolitics|website=www.realclearpolitics.com}}</ref> His mother, Veena Bhalla, owned a restaurant. She sold her successful business after the [[September 11 attacks]] and chose to serve as a civilian clinical social worker assigned to assist veterans.<ref name=\"realclearpolitics1\"/>\n\nThapar received a [[Bachelor of Science]] degree from [[Boston College]] in 1991 and a [[Juris Doctor]] from [[UC Berkeley School of Law]] in 1994.\n\n== Career ==\n=== Private practice ===\nAfter law school, Thapar served as a [[law clerk]] to [[S. Arthur Spiegel]] of the [[United States District Court for the Southern District of Ohio]] from 1994 to 1996, and then to [[Nathaniel R. Jones]] of the [[United States Court of Appeals for the Sixth Circuit]] from 1996 to 1997.<ref name=ALJreport>{{cite news |title=Nominee Report |url=https://www.afj.org/wp-content/uploads/2017/04/Thapar-Report.pdf |accessdate=9 July 2018 |publisher=[[Alliance for Justice]]}}</ref> He was an adjunct professor at the [[University of Cincinnati College of Law]] from 1995 to 1997 and from 2002 to 2006.\n\nThapar was then an attorney at the law firm of [[Williams & Connolly]] in [[Washington, D.C.]] from 1997 to 1999<ref name=ALJreport/> where he volunteered to represent the Becket Fund for Religious Liberty pro bono. In addition to being a practicing trial attorney, Thapar was also a trial advocacy instructor at the [[Georgetown University Law Center]] from 1999 to 2000.<ref name=ALJreport/> He was an [[Assistant United States Attorney]] for the [[United States District Court for the District of Columbia|District of Columbia]] from 1999 to 2000.<ref name=ALJreport/> He was general counsel to Equalfooting.com from 2000 to 2001.<ref name=ALJreport/> He returned to private practice at the [[Squire, Sanders & Dempsey]] firm in [[Cincinnati, Ohio|Cincinnati]], [[Ohio]] from 2001 to 2002 before entering a life of public service.<ref name=\"Senate Environment Committee\">{{cite web|url=http://www.epw.senate.gov/pressitem.cfm?party=rep&id=252593|title=U.S. Senate Committee on Environment and Public Works|date=|website=Epw.senate.gov|accessdate=November 26, 2016}}</ref>\n\n=== United States Attorney ===\nThapar returned to the U.S. Attorney's Office as an [[Assistant United States Attorney]] for the [[United States District Court for the Southern District of Ohio|Southern District of Ohio]] from 2002 to 2006.  He was then nominated and confirmed to the position of [[United States Attorney]] for the [[United States District Court for the Eastern District of Kentucky|Eastern District of Kentucky]], where he served from 2006 to 2007.<ref>{{cite web |title=Presidential Nomination 1345, 109th United States Congress |date=February 17, 2006 |url=https://www.congress.gov/nomination/109th-congress/1345 |publisher=[[United States Congress]] |accessdate=June 30, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.usdoj.gov/usao/kye/usattorney/index.html |title=Archived copy |access-date=December 6, 2006 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20061206184244/http://www.usdoj.gov/usao/kye/usattorney/index.html |archive-date=December 6, 2006 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nWhile an Assistant U.S. Attorney, he was appointed to the Attorney General's Advisory Committee (AGAC) and chaired the AGAC's Controlled Substances and Asset Forfeiture subcommittee. He also served on its Terrorism and National Security subcommittee, Violent Crime subcommittee, and Child Exploitation working group.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://law.vanderbilt.edu/bio/amul-thapar|title=Judge Amul Thapar {{!}} Faculty&nbsp;{{!}}&nbsp;Law School|last=|first=|date=|website=law.vanderbilt.edu|language=en|access-date=May 1, 2017}}</ref>\n\nThapar also led the Southern Ohio Mortgage Fraud Task Force, which successfully prosecuted approximately 40 perpetrators of mortgage fraud. He led the successful investigation and prosecution of a conspiracy ring to provide illegal aliens with fraudulent driver's licenses.<ref name=\"Senate Environment Committee\" />\n\n== Federal judicial service ==\n=== Service as district court judge ===\nOn May 24, 2007, Thapar was nominated by President [[George W. Bush]] for the [[United States District Court for the Eastern District of Kentucky]] seat vacated by [[Joseph Martin Hood]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Presidential Nomination 607, 110th United States Congress |date=May 24, 2007 |url=https://www.congress.gov/nomination/110th-congress/607|publisher=[[United States Congress]] |accessdate=June 30, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Rutkus, Denis Steven|first=and Bearden, Maureen|date=October 2008|title=CRS Report for Congress, Nominations to Article III Lower Courts by President George W. Bush During the 110th Congress|url=https://fas.org/sgp/crs/misc/RL33953.pdf|journal=Congressional Research Service|volume=|pages=}}</ref> The&nbsp;[[American Bar Association]]&nbsp;rated Thapar&nbsp;''Unanimously Well Qualified,''&nbsp;with one committee member abstaining.<ref>''American Bar Association'', \"[http://www.americanbar.org/content/dam/aba/migrated/2011_build/federal_judiciary/ratings110.authcheckdam.pdf Ratings of Article III Judicial Nominees, |110th Congress\"], accessed May 2, 2017.</ref>&nbsp;Thapar was confirmed by the [[United States Senate|Senate]] on December 13, 2007<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.americanbar.org/publications/governmental_affairs_periodicals/poladv_ws_07dec14.html|title=Washington Summary \u2013 ABA Governmental Affairs Office {{!}} Governmental Affairs Office|last=|first=|date=December 14, 2007|website=www.americanbar.org|access-date=May 2, 2017}}</ref> and received his commission on January 4, 2008.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=|first=|date=|title=Amul Thapar {{!}} U.S. Court of Appeals for the Sixth Circuit|url=http://www.afj.org/wp-content/uploads/2017/04/Thapar-Report.pdf|journal=AFJ Nominee Report|volume=|pages=}}</ref> The appointment made Thapar the first [[United States federal judge]] of South Asian descent.<ref name=\"nytimes.com\">{{cite news |title=The Front-Runners and Full List of Potential Supreme Court Nominees |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/06/27/us/politics/trump-list-supreme-court-nominees.html |website=The New York Times |accessdate=July 4, 2018 |language=en}}</ref> His service on the district court terminated on May 30, 2017, upon elevation to the [[United States Court of Appeals for the Sixth Circuit]].\n\nThapar began his career \"First in Ohio as a line prosecutor pursuing drug dealers, gang members, and terrorist financiers. Then in Kentucky as a U.S. attorney and a trial judge known for his work ethic, writing, and teaching: he covered 3 far-flung courthouses in his own district (Covington, London, and Pikeville), volunteered to hear additional cases in Texas and on the Sixth and Eleventh Circuits, wrote award\u2013winning opinions, and lectured regularly at UVA, Vanderbilt, Yale, Harvard, and other top schools.\"<ref name=\"yalejreg1\">{{cite web|url=http://yalejreg.com/nc/textualism-in-the-trenches-judge-amul-thapar-and-the-administrative-state-by-ben-beaton/ |title=Textualism in the Trenches: Judge Amul Thapar and the Administrative State, by Ben Beaton &#124; Notice & Comment |publisher=Yalejreg.com |date= |accessdate=2019-09-16}}</ref>\n\nAs a district court judge, Thapar heard cases in [[Covington, Kentucky|Covington]], [[Kentucky]] outside of Cincinnati, as well as in [[London, Kentucky|London]] and [[Pikeville, Kentucky|Pikeville]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.kentucky.com/news/state/article139760453.html|title=Trump to nominate federal Judge Amul Thapar to 6th Circuit Court of Appeals|last=|first=|date=|work=Kentucky.com|access-date=May 2, 2017|language=en}}</ref> While on the bench, Thapar has served as an adjunct professor at [[Vanderbilt University Law School]], [[University of Virginia School of Law]], and [[Northern Kentucky University]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/politics/2016/12/09/ky-judge-trumps-short-list-high-court/95139578/?showmenu=true|title=Ky judge on Trump's short list for high court|work=USA TODAY|access-date=May 2, 2017|language=en}}</ref> He has been an invited guest at [[Federalist Society]] programs.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fed-soc.org/experts/detail/amul-thapar|title=Hon. Amul Thapar|website=www.fed-soc.org|language=en|access-date=May 2, 2017}}</ref> Thapar was America's first federal district judge of [[South Asian]] descent.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.whitehouse.gov/the-press-office/2017/03/21/president-donald-j-trump-announces-intent-nominate-judge-amul-r-thapar|title=President Donald J. Trump Announces Intent to Nominate Judge Amul R. Thapar for the U.S. Court of Appeals for the Sixth Circuit|date=March 21, 2017|work=whitehouse.gov|access-date=May 2, 2017|language=en}}</ref><ref name=\"nytimes.com\"/>\n\nThapar is known for his folksy and engaging writing style that is meant to be understood by everyday people. In an opinion about amount in controversy requirements holding that the amount was \"exactly one penny short of the jurisdictional minimum of the federal courts\" (''Freeland v. Liberty Mut. Fire Ins. Co.'', 632 F.3d 250, 252 (6th Cir. 2011)), Thapar wrote about the humble penny, which \"tend[s] to sit at the bottom of change jars or vanish into the cracks between couch cushions.\"<ref name=\"yalejreg1\"/> In another case, Thapar explained that if the owner of a bar \"promised to pour [a] man a glass of Pappy Van Winkle\" \u2013 a rare high-end bourbon \u2013 \"but gave him a slug of Old Crow [a much lower-priced bourbon] instead, well, that would be fraud.\"<ref name=\"scotusblog1\"/>\n\n==== Notable cases as a district court judge ====\nIn 2013, Thapar was assigned to a case in the [[United States District Court for the Eastern District of Tennessee]] due to the impending retirement of [[Thomas W. Phillips (judge)|Judge Thomas Phillips]] from the Knoxville court.<ref>{{Cite journal|title=Notice|url=http://www.tned.uscourts.gov/docs/notice_ky_visiting.pdf|journal=United States District Court, Eastern District of Tennessee, Office of the Clerk|access-date=May 2, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161222161902/http://www.tned.uscourts.gov/docs/notice_ky_visiting.pdf|archive-date=December 22, 2016|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref> The case involved a high-profile break-in by peace protesters at the [[Y-12 National Security Complex]]'s Highly Enriched Uranium Materials Facility in July 2012.<ref>{{Citation|title=Us v. Walli|date=April 30, 2013|url=https://scholar.google.com/scholar_case?case=10014922571049964613&q=state+rice+thapar&hl=en&as_sdt=4,364|issue=Criminal No. 12-107-ART|accessdate=May 2, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"USA Today\" /> The three protesters, aged 57 to 82, were convicted.\n\nOn May 10, 2013, Thapar cited the definition of the federal crime of terrorism to keep the protesters in jail until their sentencing on February 18, 2014.<ref name=\"USA Today\">{{cite news|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/nation/2014/02/18/nun-nuke-protest-sentencing/5577947/ |title=Nun sentenced to 35 months in nuclear plant break-in |work=[[USA Today]] |last=Gang |first=Duane W. |date=February 18, 2014 |accessdate=February 6, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Sentencing for Y-12 Protesters Postponed until January|url=https://www.questia.com/newspaper/1P2-36363244/sentencing-for-y-12-protesters-postponed-until-january|work=[[Knoxville News Sentinel]] |date=September 13, 2013|accessdate=January 11, 2017|url-access=subscription |via=[[Questia]]}}</ref>  Thapar sentenced one of the defendants, 84-year-old nun Megan Rice, to 35 months in prison for breaking into the U.S. nuclear weapons complex and using blood to deface a bunker holding bomb-grade uranium, a demonstration that exposed serious security flaws; Rice had asked not to receive leniency and said she would be honored to receive a life sentence.<ref name=\"USA Today\" /> The two other defendants were sentenced to more than five years in prison, in part because they had much longer criminal histories. The activists' attorneys asked the judge to sentence them to time they had already served, about nine months, because of their record of goodwill. Thapar said he was concerned they showed no remorse and he wanted the punishment to be a deterrent for other activists.<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/nun-84-gets-3-years-in-prison-for-breaking-in-nuclear-weapons-complex/ |title=Nun, 84, gets 3 years in prison for breaking into nuclear weapons complex |publisher=[[CBS News]] |date=February 18, 2014 |accessdate=November 26, 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn appeal, the Sixth Circuit reversed the most serious convictions against the protesters and, in May 2015, ordered their immediate release from custody, noting that the protesters' sentencing guidelines now recommended substantially less time in custody than they had already served.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/05/27/science/sister-megan-rice-anti-nuclear-weapons-activist-freed-from-prison.html?_r=0|title=Sister Megan Rice, Freed From Prison, Looks Ahead to More Anti-Nuclear Activism|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|accessdate=November 26, 2016}}</ref>\n\n=== Service on court of appeals ===\nOn March 21, 2017, President [[Donald Trump]] nominated Thapar to the [[United States Court of Appeals for the Sixth Circuit]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Presidential Nomination 105, 115th United States Congress |date=March 21, 2017 |url=https://www.congress.gov/nomination/115th-congress/105 |publisher=[[United States Congress]] |accessdate=June 30, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.congress.gov/congressional-record/2017/03/21/senate-section/article/S1898-2|title=Congressional Record|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.whitehouse.gov/the-press-office/2017/03/21/president-trump-sends-nominations|title=President Trump Sends Nominations to the Senate|date=March 21, 2017|publisher=}}</ref> Thapar received a unanimous ''well qualified'' rating from the American Bar Association.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.americanbar.org/content/dam/aba/uncategorized/GAO/Web%20rating%20Chart%20Trump%20115.authcheckdam.pdf|title=American Bar Association Judicial Ratings|publisher=}}</ref> On April 26, 2017 the [[United States Senate Committee on the Judiciary]] held a hearing on his nomination.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.judiciary.senate.gov/meetings/04/26/2017/nominations|title=United States Senate Committee on the Judiciary|website=www.judiciary.senate.gov}}</ref> On May 18, 2017, his nomination was reported to the floor of the Senate by a party line vote of 11\u20138 with one Democrat not voting. He was confirmed by the full Senate with a vote of 52\u201344 on May 25, 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.senate.gov/legislative/LIS/roll_call_lists/roll_call_vote_cfm.cfm?congress=115&session=1&vote=00137|title=Senate roll call vote PN105|last=|first=|date=May 25, 2017|website=|publisher=United States Senate|access-date=May 26, 2017}}</ref> He received his commission on May 25, 2017. Thapar became the second [[Indian Americans|Indian American]] judge of [[United States courts of appeals]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Amul Thapar becomes second Indian-American judge of US Court of Appeals|url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/world-news/amul-thapar-becomes-second-indian-american-judge-of-us-court-of-appeals/story-ABGk1ITFmY0P8lMhoxw70O.html|publisher=[[Hindustan Times]]|date=May 26, 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe ''[[Lexington Herald-Leader]]'' reported when Thapar was nominated to the 6th Circuit that \"lawyers across the political spectrum praised [him] as a highly intellectual, thoughtful and hard-working judge.\"<ref name=\"scotusblog1\"/>\n\nThapar also speaks at law schools across the country on originalism, textualism, civility, and other topics. He teaches at the University of Virginia Law School on the judicial philosophies of Justices Scalia and Thomas.<ref name=\"realclearpolitics1\"/>\n\nIn 2018, Thapar published a law review article about the role of judges. He criticized \"pragmatic\" judging and argued that judges should not be \"politicians in robes.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://repository.law.umich.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=1694&context=mlr |title=The Pragmatism of Interpretation: A Review ofRichard A. Posner,The Federal Judiciary |last=Beaton |first=Benjamin |date=2018 |website=repository.law.umich.edu |access-date=2019-10-05}}</ref>\n\n== Consideration for the Supreme Court ==\nJudge Thapar was first considered for the Supreme Court in 2016, when he was a Federal District Judge. He has been considered a front-runner for an open seat since then. Thapar was included in a list of individuals that Republican presidential candidate [[Donald Trump]] \"would consider as potential replacements for Justice Scalia at the United States Supreme Court.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.msn.com/en-us/news/politics/donald-trump-will-expand-list-of-possible-supreme-court-picks/ar-BBwxm7M?li=BBnb7Kz|title=Donald Trump will expand list of possible Supreme Court picks|last=Flores|first=Reena|date=September 23, 2016|work=CBS News|access-date=September 23, 2016|via=MSN}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.donaldjtrump.com/press-releases/donald-j.-trump-adds-to-list-of-potential-supreme-court-justice-picks|title=Donald J. Trump Finalizes List of Potential Supreme Court Justice PicksS|website=www.donaldjtrump.com|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161008031216/https://www.donaldjtrump.com/press-releases/donald-j.-trump-adds-to-list-of-potential-supreme-court-justice-picks|archive-date=October 8, 2016|url-status=dead|access-date=May 2, 2017}}</ref>\n\nAfter the June 2018 announcement by sitting Justice [[Anthony Kennedy]] that he would retire from the court, Thapar remained on a Trump \"short-list.\"<ref>{{cite news |last1=Savage |first1=David |title=Judge Amy Coney Barrett, a potential Supreme Court nominee, has defended overturning precedents |url=https://www.latimes.com/politics/la-na-pol-court-abortion-precedent-20180703-story.html |accessdate=July 3, 2018 |publisher=LA Times |date=July 3, 2018 |quote=Judge Brett Kavanaugh, 53, a Washington veteran who serves on the U.S. Court of Appeals for the District of Columbia Circuit, and Barrett, 46, have been seen as the front-runners. White House advisors say Judges Thomas Hardiman from Pennsylvania, Raymond Kethledge from Michigan and Amul Thapar from Kentucky are also top candidates from Trump\u2019s previously announced list of 25 judges, legal scholars and politicians.}}</ref> Thapar was one of six judges interviewed by President Trump early in July while being considered to fill the Kennedy vacancy,<ref>{{cite web |last1=Roberts |first1=John |title=Trump completes interviews of Supreme Court candidates, short-list down to 6 |url=http://www.foxnews.com/politics/2018/07/05/trump-completes-interviews-supreme-court-candidates-as-short-list-shrinks.html |website=[[Fox News]] |accessdate=July 5, 2018}}</ref> which was ultimately filled by the appointment of [[Brett Kavanaugh]].\n\nThapar has been described as, \"Trump Country's Perfect SCOTUS Choice.\"<ref name=\"realclearpolitics1\"/> He would make history as the first Asian-American on the Supreme Court.<ref name=\"washingtonexaminer1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonexaminer.com/opinion/trump-should-take-a-serious-look-at-amul-thapar-for-the-supreme-court|title=Trump should take a serious look at Amul Thapar for the Supreme Court|date=July 5, 2018|website=Washington Examiner}}</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\nThapar married Kim Schulte, a Kentucky real estate agent, and converted to [[Catholicism]].<ref name=\"Courier-Journal July 2018\">{{cite web |title=Meet the Kentuckian on Trump's short list for Supreme Court justice |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/local/2018/06/28/meet-trump-supreme-court-nominee-amul-thapar/742481002/ |website=USA TODAY |accessdate=July 4, 2018 |language=en}}</ref><ref name=\"SCOTUSblog\"/> The couple reside in [[Covington, Kentucky]] with their three children.<ref name=\"SCOTUSblog\"/>\n\nThapar engages in his community through volunteer work. At his confirmation hearing, Senator [[Mitch McConnell]] noted that Thapar had \"founded a brand-new chapter of the well-respected Street Law program, which sends law school students into underprivileged high schools to teach the basic underpinnings of our legal system.\"<ref name=\"scotusblog1\"/>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Donald Trump Supreme Court candidates]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{FJC Bio|nid=1392666}}\n* {{Ballotpedia|Amul_Thapar|Amul Thapar}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20120510104547/http://www.law.virginia.edu/lawweb/faculty.nsf/0/0BEFFFE8FD93AF248525795A007398D6 Biography at University of Virginia School of Law]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20111020204106/http://chaselaw.nku.edu/faculty/adjunct_faculty/adjunct_bio.php?id=186 Biography at Northern Kentucky (archived)]\n* [http://www.ca6.uscourts.gov/ United States Court of Appeals for the Sixth Circuit Official Website]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20150925211148/http://www.knoxnews.com/news/local-news/y-12-protesters-must-stay-jail-judge-rules Knoxville News Sentinel article, 5/11/2013]\n* [https://www.judiciary.senate.gov/imo/media/doc/Thapar%20SJQ%20Public.pdf Questionnaire for Judicial Nominees] for the [[United States Senate Committee on the Judiciary]]\t\n* [https://fedsoc.org/contributors/amul-thapar Contributor profile] from the [[Federalist Society]]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-legal}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Gregory F. Van Tatenhove]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title={{nowrap|[[United States Attorney]] for the [[United States District Court for the Eastern District of Kentucky|Eastern District of Kentucky]]}}|years=2006\u20132008}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Kerry B. Harvey]]}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Joseph Martin Hood]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title={{nowrap|Judge of the [[United States District Court for the Eastern District of Kentucky]]}}|years=2008\u20132017}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Robert E. Wier]]}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Boyce F. Martin Jr.]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title={{nowrap|Judge of the [[United States Court of Appeals for the Sixth Circuit]]}}|years=2017\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{United States courts of appeals judges}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Thapar, Amul Roger}}\n[[Category:1969 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:20th-century American lawyers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American lawyers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American judges]]\n[[Category:American jurists of Indian descent]]\n[[Category:American people of Indian descent]]\n[[Category:American Roman Catholics]]\n[[Category:Assistant United States Attorneys]]\n[[Category:Boston College alumni]]\n[[Category:Converts to Roman Catholicism from Hinduism]]\n[[Category:Federalist Society members]]\n[[Category:George W. Bush administration personnel]]\n[[Category:Georgetown University faculty]]\n[[Category:Judges of the United States District Court for the Eastern District of Kentucky]]\n[[Category:Judges of the United States Court of Appeals for the Sixth Circuit]]\n[[Category:Kentucky lawyers]]\n[[Category:Lawyers from Detroit]]\n[[Category:United States Attorneys for the Eastern District of Kentucky]]\n[[Category:United States district court judges appointed by George W. Bush]]\n[[Category:United States court of appeals judges appointed by Donald Trump]]\n[[Category:University of California, Berkeley alumni]]\n[[Category:University of Cincinnati College of Law faculty]]\n[[Category:University of Virginia School of Law faculty]]\n[[Category:People from Covington, Kentucky]]\n", "text_old": "{{Short description|American judge}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=July 2018}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name         = Amul Thapar\n| image        = Amul Thapar.jpg\n| office       = Judge of the [[United States Court of Appeals for the Sixth Circuit]]\n| appointer    = [[List of federal judges appointed by Donald Trump|Donald Trump]]\n| term_start   = May 25, 2017\n| term_end     =\n| predecessor  = [[Boyce F. Martin Jr.]]\n| successor    =\n| office1      = Judge of the [[United States District Court for the Eastern District of Kentucky]]\n| appointer1   = [[List of federal judges appointed by George W. Bush|George W. Bush]]\n| term_start1  = January 4, 2008\n| term_end1    = May 30, 2017\n| predecessor1 = [[Joseph Martin Hood]]\n| successor1   = [[Robert E. Wier]]\n| office2      = [[United States Attorney]] for the [[United States District Court for the Eastern District of Kentucky|Eastern District of Kentucky]]\n| president2   = [[George W. Bush]]\n| term_start2  = March 20, 2006\n| term_end2    = January 2008\n| predecessor2 = [[Gregory F. Van Tatenhove]]\n| successor2   = [[Kerry B. Harvey]]\n| birth_name   = Amul Roger Thapar\n| birth_date   = {{Birth date and age|1969|04|29}}\n| birth_place  = [[Troy, Michigan|Troy]], [[Michigan]], U.S.\n| death_date   =\n| death_place  =\n| education    = [[Boston College]] ([[Bachelor of Science|BS]])<br>{{nowrap|[[UC Berkeley School of Law]] ([[Juris Doctor|JD]])}}\n| party        =\n}}\n'''Amul Roger Thapar''' (born April 29, 1969) is a [[United States federal judge|United States Circuit Judge]] of the [[United States Court of Appeals for the Sixth Circuit]]. He is a former [[United States federal judge|United States District Judge]] of the [[United States District Court for the Eastern District of Kentucky]] and former [[United States Attorney]] for the Eastern District of Kentucky. Thapar was the first South Asian federal judge in American history.  He was also President Trump's first Court of Appeals appointment and Trump's second judicial appointment after Justice [[Neil Gorsuch]]. Thapar is frequently discussed as a short-lister for the Supreme Court of the United States.\n\n== Early life and education ==\nThapar has lived most of his life in the midwest.<ref name=\"scotusblog1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.scotusblog.com/2018/07/potential-nominee-profile-amul-thapar/ |title=Potential nominee profile: Amul Thapar |publisher=SCOTUSblog |date=2018-07-03 |accessdate=2019-09-16}}</ref> He was born in [[Troy, Michigan|Troy]], [[Michigan]] to parents who immigrated from [[India]]. He was raised in [[Toledo, Ohio]],<ref name=\"SCOTUSblog\">{{cite web |title=Potential nominee profile: Amul Thapar |url=http://www.scotusblog.com/2018/07/potential-nominee-profile-amul-thapar/ |website=[[SCOTUSblog]] |accessdate=July 4, 2018 |date=July 3, 2018}}</ref> where his father, Raj Thapar, owns a heating and air-conditioning supply business.<ref name=\"Courier-Journal December 2016\">{{cite web |title=Ky judge on Trump's short list for high court |url=https://www.courier-journal.com/story/news/politics/2016/12/09/ky-judge-trumps-short-list-high-court/95139578/ |website=The Courier-Journal |accessdate=July 4, 2018 |language=en}}</ref> Thapar worked for his father's business driving the truck.<ref name=\"realclearpolitics1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.realclearpolitics.com/articles/2018/07/03/amul_thapar_trump_countrys_perfect_scotus_choice_137420.html|title=Amul Thapar: Trump Country's Perfect SCOTUS Choice &#124; RealClearPolitics|website=www.realclearpolitics.com}}</ref> His mother, Veena Bhalla, owned a restaurant. She sold her successful business after the [[September 11 attacks]] and chose to serve as a civilian clinical social worker assigned to assist veterans.<ref name=\"realclearpolitics1\"/>\n\n\nThapar received a [[Bachelor of Science]] degree from [[Boston College]] in 1991 and a [[Juris Doctor]] from [[UC Berkeley School of Law]] in 1994.\n\n== Career ==\n=== Private practice ===\nAfter law school, Thapar served as a [[law clerk]] to [[S. Arthur Spiegel]] of the [[United States District Court for the Southern District of Ohio]] from 1994 to 1996, and then to [[Nathaniel R. Jones]] of the [[United States Court of Appeals for the Sixth Circuit]] from 1996 to 1997.<ref name=ALJreport>{{cite news |title=Nominee Report |url=https://www.afj.org/wp-content/uploads/2017/04/Thapar-Report.pdf |accessdate=9 July 2018 |publisher=[[Alliance for Justice]]}}</ref> He was an adjunct professor at the [[University of Cincinnati College of Law]] from 1995 to 1997 and from 2002 to 2006.\n\nThapar was then an attorney at the law firm of [[Williams & Connolly]] in [[Washington, D.C.]] from 1997 to 1999<ref name=ALJreport/> where he volunteered to represent the Becket Fund for Religious Liberty pro bono. In addition to being a practicing trial attorney, Thapar was also a trial advocacy instructor at the [[Georgetown University Law Center]] from 1999 to 2000.<ref name=ALJreport/> He was an [[Assistant United States Attorney]] for the [[United States District Court for the District of Columbia|District of Columbia]] from 1999 to 2000.<ref name=ALJreport/> He was general counsel to Equalfooting.com from 2000 to 2001.<ref name=ALJreport/> He returned to private practice at the [[Squire, Sanders & Dempsey]] firm in [[Cincinnati, Ohio|Cincinnati]], [[Ohio]] from 2001 to 2002 before entering a life of public service.<ref name=\"Senate Environment Committee\">{{cite web|url=http://www.epw.senate.gov/pressitem.cfm?party=rep&id=252593|title=U.S. Senate Committee on Environment and Public Works|date=|website=Epw.senate.gov|accessdate=November 26, 2016}}</ref>\n\n=== United States Attorney ===\nThapar returned to the U.S. Attorney's Office as an [[Assistant United States Attorney]] for the [[United States District Court for the Southern District of Ohio|Southern District of Ohio]] from 2002 to 2006.  He was then nominated and confirmed to the position of [[United States Attorney]] for the [[United States District Court for the Eastern District of Kentucky|Eastern District of Kentucky]], where he served from 2006 to 2007.<ref>{{cite web |title=Presidential Nomination 1345, 109th United States Congress |date=February 17, 2006 |url=https://www.congress.gov/nomination/109th-congress/1345 |publisher=[[United States Congress]] |accessdate=June 30, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.usdoj.gov/usao/kye/usattorney/index.html |title=Archived copy |access-date=December 6, 2006 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20061206184244/http://www.usdoj.gov/usao/kye/usattorney/index.html |archive-date=December 6, 2006 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nWhile an Assistant U.S. Attorney, he was appointed to the Attorney General's Advisory Committee (AGAC) and chaired the AGAC's Controlled Substances and Asset Forfeiture subcommittee. He also served on its Terrorism and National Security subcommittee, Violent Crime subcommittee, and Child Exploitation working group.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://law.vanderbilt.edu/bio/amul-thapar|title=Judge Amul Thapar {{!}} Faculty&nbsp;{{!}}&nbsp;Law School|last=|first=|date=|website=law.vanderbilt.edu|language=en|access-date=May 1, 2017}}</ref>\n\nThapar also led the Southern Ohio Mortgage Fraud Task Force, which successfully prosecuted approximately 40 perpetrators of mortgage fraud. He led the successful investigation and prosecution of a conspiracy ring to provide illegal aliens with fraudulent driver's licenses.<ref name=\"Senate Environment Committee\" />\n\n== Federal judicial service ==\n=== Service as district court judge ===\nOn May 24, 2007, Thapar was nominated by President [[George W. Bush]] for the [[United States District Court for the Eastern District of Kentucky]] seat vacated by [[Joseph Martin Hood]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Presidential Nomination 607, 110th United States Congress |date=May 24, 2007 |url=https://www.congress.gov/nomination/110th-congress/607|publisher=[[United States Congress]] |accessdate=June 30, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Rutkus, Denis Steven|first=and Bearden, Maureen|date=October 2008|title=CRS Report for Congress, Nominations to Article III Lower Courts by President George W. Bush During the 110th Congress|url=https://fas.org/sgp/crs/misc/RL33953.pdf|journal=Congressional Research Service|volume=|pages=}}</ref> The&nbsp;[[American Bar Association]]&nbsp;rated Thapar&nbsp;''Unanimously Well Qualified,''&nbsp;with one committee member abstaining.<ref>''American Bar Association'', \"[http://www.americanbar.org/content/dam/aba/migrated/2011_build/federal_judiciary/ratings110.authcheckdam.pdf Ratings of Article III Judicial Nominees, |110th Congress\"], accessed May 2, 2017.</ref>&nbsp;Thapar was confirmed by the [[United States Senate|Senate]] on December 13, 2007<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.americanbar.org/publications/governmental_affairs_periodicals/poladv_ws_07dec14.html|title=Washington Summary \u2013 ABA Governmental Affairs Office {{!}} Governmental Affairs Office|last=|first=|date=December 14, 2007|website=www.americanbar.org|access-date=May 2, 2017}}</ref> and received his commission on January 4, 2008.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=|first=|date=|title=Amul Thapar {{!}} U.S. Court of Appeals for the Sixth Circuit|url=http://www.afj.org/wp-content/uploads/2017/04/Thapar-Report.pdf|journal=AFJ Nominee Report|volume=|pages=}}</ref> The appointment made Thapar the first [[United States federal judge]] of South Asian descent.<ref name=\"nytimes.com\">{{cite news |title=The Front-Runners and Full List of Potential Supreme Court Nominees |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/06/27/us/politics/trump-list-supreme-court-nominees.html |website=The New York Times |accessdate=July 4, 2018 |language=en}}</ref> His service on the district court terminated on May 30, 2017, upon elevation to the [[United States Court of Appeals for the Sixth Circuit]].\n\nThapar began his career \"First in Ohio as a line prosecutor pursuing drug dealers, gang members, and terrorist financiers. Then in Kentucky as a U.S. attorney and a trial judge known for his work ethic, writing, and teaching: he covered 3 far-flung courthouses in his own district (Covington, London, and Pikeville), volunteered to hear additional cases in Texas and on the Sixth and Eleventh Circuits, wrote award\u2013winning opinions, and lectured regularly at UVA, Vanderbilt, Yale, Harvard, and other top schools.\"<ref name=\"yalejreg1\">{{cite web|url=http://yalejreg.com/nc/textualism-in-the-trenches-judge-amul-thapar-and-the-administrative-state-by-ben-beaton/ |title=Textualism in the Trenches: Judge Amul Thapar and the Administrative State, by Ben Beaton &#124; Notice & Comment |publisher=Yalejreg.com |date= |accessdate=2019-09-16}}</ref>\n\nAs a district court judge, Thapar heard cases in [[Covington, Kentucky|Covington]], [[Kentucky]] outside of Cincinnati, as well as in [[London, Kentucky|London]] and [[Pikeville, Kentucky|Pikeville]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.kentucky.com/news/state/article139760453.html|title=Trump to nominate federal Judge Amul Thapar to 6th Circuit Court of Appeals|last=|first=|date=|work=Kentucky.com|access-date=May 2, 2017|language=en}}</ref> While on the bench, Thapar has served as an adjunct professor at [[Vanderbilt University Law School]], [[University of Virginia School of Law]], and [[Northern Kentucky University]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/politics/2016/12/09/ky-judge-trumps-short-list-high-court/95139578/?showmenu=true|title=Ky judge on Trump's short list for high court|work=USA TODAY|access-date=May 2, 2017|language=en}}</ref> He has been an invited guest at [[Federalist Society]] programs.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fed-soc.org/experts/detail/amul-thapar|title=Hon. Amul Thapar|website=www.fed-soc.org|language=en|access-date=May 2, 2017}}</ref> Thapar was America's first federal district judge of [[South Asian]] descent.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.whitehouse.gov/the-press-office/2017/03/21/president-donald-j-trump-announces-intent-nominate-judge-amul-r-thapar|title=President Donald J. Trump Announces Intent to Nominate Judge Amul R. Thapar for the U.S. Court of Appeals for the Sixth Circuit|date=March 21, 2017|work=whitehouse.gov|access-date=May 2, 2017|language=en}}</ref><ref name=\"nytimes.com\"/>\n\nThapar is known for his folksy and engaging writing style that is meant to be understood by everyday people. In an opinion about amount in controversy requirements holding that the amount was \"exactly one penny short of the jurisdictional minimum of the federal courts\" (''Freeland v. Liberty Mut. Fire Ins. Co.'', 632 F.3d 250, 252 (6th Cir. 2011)), Thapar wrote about the humble penny, which \"tend[s] to sit at the bottom of change jars or vanish into the cracks between couch cushions.\"<ref name=\"yalejreg1\"/> In another case, Thapar explained that if the owner of a bar \"promised to pour [a] man a glass of Pappy Van Winkle\" \u2013 a rare high-end bourbon \u2013 \"but gave him a slug of Old Crow [a much lower-priced bourbon] instead, well, that would be fraud.\"<ref name=\"scotusblog1\"/>\n\n==== Notable cases as a district court judge ====\nIn 2013, Thapar was assigned to a case in the [[United States District Court for the Eastern District of Tennessee]] due to the impending retirement of [[Thomas W. Phillips (judge)|Judge Thomas Phillips]] from the Knoxville court.<ref>{{Cite journal|title=Notice|url=http://www.tned.uscourts.gov/docs/notice_ky_visiting.pdf|journal=United States District Court, Eastern District of Tennessee, Office of the Clerk|access-date=May 2, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161222161902/http://www.tned.uscourts.gov/docs/notice_ky_visiting.pdf|archive-date=December 22, 2016|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref> The case involved a high-profile break-in by peace protesters at the [[Y-12 National Security Complex]]'s Highly Enriched Uranium Materials Facility in July 2012.<ref>{{Citation|title=Us v. Walli|date=April 30, 2013|url=https://scholar.google.com/scholar_case?case=10014922571049964613&q=state+rice+thapar&hl=en&as_sdt=4,364|issue=Criminal No. 12-107-ART|accessdate=May 2, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"USA Today\" /> The three protesters, aged 57 to 82, were convicted.\n\nOn May 10, 2013, Thapar cited the definition of the federal crime of terrorism to keep the protesters in jail until their sentencing on February 18, 2014.<ref name=\"USA Today\">{{cite news|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/nation/2014/02/18/nun-nuke-protest-sentencing/5577947/ |title=Nun sentenced to 35 months in nuclear plant break-in |work=[[USA Today]] |last=Gang |first=Duane W. |date=February 18, 2014 |accessdate=February 6, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Sentencing for Y-12 Protesters Postponed until January|url=https://www.questia.com/newspaper/1P2-36363244/sentencing-for-y-12-protesters-postponed-until-january|work=[[Knoxville News Sentinel]] |date=September 13, 2013|accessdate=January 11, 2017|url-access=subscription |via=[[Questia]]}}</ref>  Thapar sentenced one of the defendants, 84-year-old nun Megan Rice, to 35 months in prison for breaking into the U.S. nuclear weapons complex and using blood to deface a bunker holding bomb-grade uranium, a demonstration that exposed serious security flaws; Rice had asked not to receive leniency and said she would be honored to receive a life sentence.<ref name=\"USA Today\" /> The two other defendants were sentenced to more than five years in prison, in part because they had much longer criminal histories. The activists' attorneys asked the judge to sentence them to time they had already served, about nine months, because of their record of goodwill. Thapar said he was concerned they showed no remorse and he wanted the punishment to be a deterrent for other activists.<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/nun-84-gets-3-years-in-prison-for-breaking-in-nuclear-weapons-complex/ |title=Nun, 84, gets 3 years in prison for breaking into nuclear weapons complex |publisher=[[CBS News]] |date=February 18, 2014 |accessdate=November 26, 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn appeal, the Sixth Circuit reversed the most serious convictions against the protesters and, in May 2015, ordered their immediate release from custody, noting that the protesters' sentencing guidelines now recommended substantially less time in custody than they had already served.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/05/27/science/sister-megan-rice-anti-nuclear-weapons-activist-freed-from-prison.html?_r=0|title=Sister Megan Rice, Freed From Prison, Looks Ahead to More Anti-Nuclear Activism|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|accessdate=November 26, 2016}}</ref>\n\n=== Service on court of appeals ===\nOn March 21, 2017, President [[Donald Trump]] nominated Thapar to the [[United States Court of Appeals for the Sixth Circuit]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Presidential Nomination 105, 115th United States Congress |date=March 21, 2017 |url=https://www.congress.gov/nomination/115th-congress/105 |publisher=[[United States Congress]] |accessdate=June 30, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.congress.gov/congressional-record/2017/03/21/senate-section/article/S1898-2|title=Congressional Record|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.whitehouse.gov/the-press-office/2017/03/21/president-trump-sends-nominations|title=President Trump Sends Nominations to the Senate|date=March 21, 2017|publisher=}}</ref> Thapar received a unanimous ''well qualified'' rating from the American Bar Association.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.americanbar.org/content/dam/aba/uncategorized/GAO/Web%20rating%20Chart%20Trump%20115.authcheckdam.pdf|title=American Bar Association Judicial Ratings|publisher=}}</ref> On April 26, 2017 the [[United States Senate Committee on the Judiciary]] held a hearing on his nomination.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.judiciary.senate.gov/meetings/04/26/2017/nominations|title=United States Senate Committee on the Judiciary|website=www.judiciary.senate.gov}}</ref> On May 18, 2017, his nomination was reported to the floor of the Senate by a party line vote of 11\u20138 with one Democrat not voting. He was confirmed by the full Senate with a vote of 52\u201344 on May 25, 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.senate.gov/legislative/LIS/roll_call_lists/roll_call_vote_cfm.cfm?congress=115&session=1&vote=00137|title=Senate roll call vote PN105|last=|first=|date=May 25, 2017|website=|publisher=United States Senate|access-date=May 26, 2017}}</ref> He received his commission on May 25, 2017. Thapar became the second [[Indian Americans|Indian American]] judge of [[United States courts of appeals]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Amul Thapar becomes second Indian-American judge of US Court of Appeals|url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/world-news/amul-thapar-becomes-second-indian-american-judge-of-us-court-of-appeals/story-ABGk1ITFmY0P8lMhoxw70O.html|publisher=[[Hindustan Times]]|date=May 26, 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe ''[[Lexington Herald-Leader]]'' reported when Thapar was nominated to the 6th Circuit that \"lawyers across the political spectrum praised [him] as a highly intellectual, thoughtful and hard-working judge.\"<ref name=\"scotusblog1\"/>\n\nThapar also speaks at law schools across the country on originalism, textualism, civility, and other topics. He teaches at the University of Virginia Law School on the judicial philosophies of Justices Scalia and Thomas.<ref name=\"realclearpolitics1\"/>\n\nIn 2018, Thapar published a law review article about the role of judges. He criticized \"pragmatic\" judging and argued that judges should not be \"politicians in robes.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://repository.law.umich.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=1694&context=mlr |title=The Pragmatism of Interpretation: A Review ofRichard A. Posner,The Federal Judiciary |last=Beaton |first=Benjamin |date=2018 |website=repository.law.umich.edu |access-date=2019-10-05}}</ref>\n\n== Consideration for the Supreme Court ==\nJudge Thapar was first considered for the Supreme Court in 2016, when he was a Federal District Judge. He has been considered a front-runner for an open seat since then. Thapar was included in a list of individuals that Republican presidential candidate [[Donald Trump]] \"would consider as potential replacements for Justice Scalia at the United States Supreme Court.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.msn.com/en-us/news/politics/donald-trump-will-expand-list-of-possible-supreme-court-picks/ar-BBwxm7M?li=BBnb7Kz|title=Donald Trump will expand list of possible Supreme Court picks|last=Flores|first=Reena|date=September 23, 2016|work=CBS News|access-date=September 23, 2016|via=MSN}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.donaldjtrump.com/press-releases/donald-j.-trump-adds-to-list-of-potential-supreme-court-justice-picks|title=Donald J. Trump Finalizes List of Potential Supreme Court Justice PicksS|website=www.donaldjtrump.com|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161008031216/https://www.donaldjtrump.com/press-releases/donald-j.-trump-adds-to-list-of-potential-supreme-court-justice-picks|archive-date=October 8, 2016|url-status=dead|access-date=May 2, 2017}}</ref>\n\nAfter the June 2018 announcement by sitting Justice [[Anthony Kennedy]] that he would retire from the court, Thapar remained on a Trump \"short-list.\"<ref>{{cite news |last1=Savage |first1=David |title=Judge Amy Coney Barrett, a potential Supreme Court nominee, has defended overturning precedents |url=https://www.latimes.com/politics/la-na-pol-court-abortion-precedent-20180703-story.html |accessdate=July 3, 2018 |publisher=LA Times |date=July 3, 2018 |quote=Judge Brett Kavanaugh, 53, a Washington veteran who serves on the U.S. Court of Appeals for the District of Columbia Circuit, and Barrett, 46, have been seen as the front-runners. White House advisors say Judges Thomas Hardiman from Pennsylvania, Raymond Kethledge from Michigan and Amul Thapar from Kentucky are also top candidates from Trump\u2019s previously announced list of 25 judges, legal scholars and politicians.}}</ref> Thapar was one of six judges interviewed by President Trump early in July while being considered to fill the Kennedy vacancy,<ref>{{cite web |last1=Roberts |first1=John |title=Trump completes interviews of Supreme Court candidates, short-list down to 6 |url=http://www.foxnews.com/politics/2018/07/05/trump-completes-interviews-supreme-court-candidates-as-short-list-shrinks.html |website=[[Fox News]] |accessdate=July 5, 2018}}</ref> which was ultimately filled by the appointment of [[Brett Kavanaugh]].\n\nThapar has been described as, \"Trump Country's Perfect SCOTUS Choice.\"<ref name=\"realclearpolitics1\"/> He would make history as the first Asian-American on the Supreme Court.<ref name=\"washingtonexaminer1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonexaminer.com/opinion/trump-should-take-a-serious-look-at-amul-thapar-for-the-supreme-court|title=Trump should take a serious look at Amul Thapar for the Supreme Court|date=July 5, 2018|website=Washington Examiner}}</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\nThapar married Kim Schulte, a Kentucky real estate agent, and converted to [[Catholicism]].<ref name=\"Courier-Journal July 2018\">{{cite web |title=Meet the Kentuckian on Trump's short list for Supreme Court justice |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/local/2018/06/28/meet-trump-supreme-court-nominee-amul-thapar/742481002/ |website=USA TODAY |accessdate=July 4, 2018 |language=en}}</ref><ref name=\"SCOTUSblog\"/> The couple reside in [[Covington, Kentucky]] with their three children.<ref name=\"SCOTUSblog\"/>\n\nThapar engages in his community through volunteer work. At his confirmation hearing, Senator [[Mitch McConnell]] noted that Thapar had \"founded a brand-new chapter of the well-respected Street Law program, which sends law school students into underprivileged high schools to teach the basic underpinnings of our legal system.\"<ref name=\"scotusblog1\"/>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Donald Trump Supreme Court candidates]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{FJC Bio|nid=1392666}}\n* {{Ballotpedia|Amul_Thapar|Amul Thapar}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20120510104547/http://www.law.virginia.edu/lawweb/faculty.nsf/0/0BEFFFE8FD93AF248525795A007398D6 Biography at University of Virginia School of Law]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20111020204106/http://chaselaw.nku.edu/faculty/adjunct_faculty/adjunct_bio.php?id=186 Biography at Northern Kentucky (archived)]\n* [http://www.ca6.uscourts.gov/ United States Court of Appeals for the Sixth Circuit Official Website]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20150925211148/http://www.knoxnews.com/news/local-news/y-12-protesters-must-stay-jail-judge-rules Knoxville News Sentinel article, 5/11/2013]\n* [https://www.judiciary.senate.gov/imo/media/doc/Thapar%20SJQ%20Public.pdf Questionnaire for Judicial Nominees] for the [[United States Senate Committee on the Judiciary]]\t\n* [https://fedsoc.org/contributors/amul-thapar Contributor profile] from the [[Federalist Society]]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-legal}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Gregory F. Van Tatenhove]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title={{nowrap|[[United States Attorney]] for the [[United States District Court for the Eastern District of Kentucky|Eastern District of Kentucky]]}}|years=2006\u20132008}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Kerry B. Harvey]]}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Joseph Martin Hood]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title={{nowrap|Judge of the [[United States District Court for the Eastern District of Kentucky]]}}|years=2008\u20132017}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Robert E. Wier]]}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Boyce F. Martin Jr.]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title={{nowrap|Judge of the [[United States Court of Appeals for the Sixth Circuit]]}}|years=2017\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{United States courts of appeals judges}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Thapar, Amul Roger}}\n[[Category:1969 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:20th-century American lawyers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American lawyers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American judges]]\n[[Category:American jurists of Indian descent]]\n[[Category:American people of Indian descent]]\n[[Category:American Roman Catholics]]\n[[Category:Assistant United States Attorneys]]\n[[Category:Boston College alumni]]\n[[Category:Converts to Roman Catholicism from Hinduism]]\n[[Category:Federalist Society members]]\n[[Category:George W. Bush administration personnel]]\n[[Category:Georgetown University faculty]]\n[[Category:Judges of the United States District Court for the Eastern District of Kentucky]]\n[[Category:Judges of the United States Court of Appeals for the Sixth Circuit]]\n[[Category:Kentucky lawyers]]\n[[Category:Lawyers from Detroit]]\n[[Category:United States Attorneys for the Eastern District of Kentucky]]\n[[Category:United States district court judges appoi